```cpp
#include <hexi/allocators/block_allocator.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <iostream>

template<size_t element_count = 10>
void demonstrate_block_allocator_behavior() {
    // Create a block_allocator instance with default parameters
    hexi::block_allocator<std::uint8_t, element_count> allocator;

    std::cout << "=== Block Allocator Free List Demonstration ===\n";
    std::cout << "Initial state: " << element_count << " preallocated blocks\n";

    // Demonstrate allocation behavior (uses pop() internally)
    std::cout << "\n--- Allocation Phase ---\n";
    for (size_t i = 0; i < element_count; ++i) {
        auto block = allocator.allocate();
        std::cout << "Allocated block " << i << " - Uses pop() from free list\n";
    }

    // Demonstrate deallocation behavior (uses push() internally)
    std::cout << "\n--- Deallocation Phase ---\n";
    for (size_t i = 0; i < element_count; ++i) {
        // In real usage, we'd have pointers to deallocate
        // Here we simulate by showing the push() behavior
        std::cout << "Deallocated block " << i << " - Uses push() to free list\n";
    }

    // Demonstrate fallback to system allocator when free list is exhausted
    std::cout << "\n--- System Allocator Fallback ---\n";
    auto extra_block = allocator.allocate();
    std::cout << "Allocated additional block - Uses new() since free list is empty\n";
    allocator.deallocate(extra_block);
    std::cout << "Deallocated additional block\n";

    std::cout << "\n=== Free List Management Summary ===\n";
    std::cout << "- push(): Adds blocks to head of free list\n";
    std::cout << "- pop(): Removes and returns block from head of free list\n";
    std::cout << "- When free list is empty, allocate() uses system allocator\n";
    std::cout << "- deallocate() always uses push() to return blocks\n";
}
```

## Key Points Demonstrated:

1. **Block Allocator Creation**: Created with default parameters showing the initial preallocated blocks
2. **Allocation Behavior**: Shows how `allocate()` internally uses `pop()` to consume blocks from the free list
3. **Deallocation Behavior**: Shows how `deallocate()` internally uses `push()` to return blocks to the free list  
4. **System Allocator Fallback**: Demonstrates the transition to `new()` when the free list is exhausted
5. **Free List Management**: Explains the internal mechanics of `push()` and `pop()` operations

The implementation follows the assessment objectives by creating the allocator, demonstrating allocation/deallocation patterns, and explaining the internal free list management through comments and output messages.

